{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774428654,"nonce":"YPaRnfu8XOyLE6lXhSCKPy9buSU=","message":"**Fine ratio sweep results: sharp transition at r=0.10-0.12**\n\n| ratio | vel(S=0.5) | ep_err | Δvel% |\n|-------|-----------|--------|-------|\n| 0.10 | 2.00 | 0.158 | +4.8% |\n| 0.12 | 1.94 | 0.003 | +0.3% |\n| 0.15 | 1.97 | 0.003 | +0.1% |\n| 0.18 | 2.01 | 0.005 | -0.1% |\n| 0.20 | 2.04 | 0.004 | +0.4% |\n\nThe SISU velocity effect exists ONLY when the model is at the edge of task failure (r=0.10, ep_err=0.158). At r≥0.12, reaching is competent and the SISU effect vanishes. No intermediate regime exists where both reaching works AND SISU modulates velocity.\n\nThis is a strong negative result for the control cost balancing approach: there is no \"sweet spot\" ratio. The mechanism is that a severely constrained model develops SISU-dependent behavior as an artifact of being near its performance limit, not as a deliberate robust control strategy.\n\nMinimax adversarial training is running as the next approach to test.","files":null}]}